Tree-sitter parse all files in a project for specified rebar.config file

Usage: elp parse-elp [OPTIONS]

Options:
      --project <PROJECT>    Path to directory with project, or to a JSON file [default: .]
      --module <MODULE>      Parse a single module from the project, not the entire project
      --file <FILE>          Parse a single file from the project, not the entire project. \nThis
                             can be an include file or escript, etc
      --to <TO>              Path to a directory where to dump result files
      --no-diags             Do not print the full diagnostics for a file, just the count
      --experimental         Report experimental diagnostics too, if diagnostics are enabled
      --as <PROFILE>         Rebar3 profile to pickup [default: test]
      --dump-includes        Report the resolution of include directives for comparison with OTP
                             ones
      --rebar                Run with rebar
      --include-generated    Also process generated modules
      --serial               Parse the files serially, not in parallel
      --use-cli-severity     If specified, use the provided CLI severity mapping instead of the
                             default one
      --format <FORMAT>      Customize the output format (defaults to human-readable) [possible
                             values: json]
      --report-system-stats  Report system memory usage and other statistics
      --severity <SEVERITY>  Minimum severity level to report [possible values: error, warning,
                             weak_warning, information]
  -h, --help                 Print help

Global options:
      --log-file <LOG_FILE>  
      --erl <ERL>            
      --escript <ESCRIPT>    
      --no-log-buffering     
      --no-buck-generated    When using buck, do not invoke a build step for generated files
      --buck-quick-start     Use buck2 targets for first stage project loading
      --ifdef                Enable ifdef/ifndef condition evaluation (experimental)
      --color <WHEN>         Use color in output [default: always] [possible values: always, never,
                             auto]
